<m0>y wife Lynda and I were taking a Saturday jog on the beach when she suddenly doubled over from a wave of nausea.<ep>
   ``I swear it feels like morning sickness,'' she said.<ep>
   I could think of no response other than, ``Heh, heh, heh.''<ep>
   We're in our mid-40s, and folks our age don't even think about having babies. The factory's closed. The crew's laid off. We're reproductively downsized. So ``heh, heh, heh'' was the best I could manage.<ep>
   Still, stranger things have happened (--) we could've been hit by errant fertility rays from the mother ship meant for Madonna. So we went on yellow alert, keeping a loose eye on the situation, but remaining steadfastly in denial until conditions reverted to green.<ep>
   The mistake I made was joking about it with our daughter Sarah, 11.<ep>
   ``Mom's got morning sickness,'' I said.<ep>
   ``That's not even funny,'' Sarah answered.<ep>
   ``Well, she said it seemed like <m2><ql>
